1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,985
In this demo, we'll be looking at a synthetic dataset of

2
00:00:02,985 --> 00:00:07,800
Phase 2 clinical trial data for a new innovative oral insulin called Auralin,

3
00:00:07,800 --> 00:00:11,430
a proprietary capsule that can solve stomach lining issues.

4
00:00:11,430 --> 00:00:14,925
Three hundred and fifty patients are participating in this trial.

5
00:00:14,925 --> 00:00:17,790
Half of the patients are being treated with Auralin and the other

6
00:00:17,790 --> 00:00:21,825
175 being treated with a popular injectable insulin called Novodra.

7
00:00:21,825 --> 00:00:24,585
By comparing key metrics between these two drugs,

8
00:00:24,585 --> 00:00:26,850
we can determine if Auralin is effective.

9
00:00:26,850 --> 00:00:30,690
Now note that Auralin and Novodra are not real insulin products.

10
00:00:30,690 --> 00:00:35,220
This clinical trial data was fabricated with the consultation of real doctors to ensure

11
00:00:35,220 --> 00:00:37,815
plausibility and reflecting real data issues

12
00:00:37,815 --> 00:00:40,650
in the healthcare domain for the purposes of this course.

13
00:00:40,650 --> 00:00:43,910
Phase 2 trials are intended to test the efficacy and

14
00:00:43,910 --> 00:00:47,680
the dose-response of a drug and identify adverse reactions.

15
00:00:47,680 --> 00:00:52,250
We have three data tables as part of this dataset, the patient's table,

16
00:00:52,250 --> 00:00:55,325
which is giving us important information about our hypothetical patients,

17
00:00:55,325 --> 00:00:56,675
like their gender, name,

18
00:00:56,675 --> 00:00:59,695
height, weight, address, etc,

19
00:00:59,695 --> 00:01:02,570
the treatments table, which is providing us with

20
00:01:02,570 --> 00:01:05,675
information on the detailed treatment information.

21
00:01:05,675 --> 00:01:09,830
This table includes the names of patients who participated in clinical trials,

22
00:01:09,830 --> 00:01:12,980
the dosage of Auralin and Novodra and the patient's blood

23
00:01:12,980 --> 00:01:17,155
sugar or hemoglobin levels indicated by HbA1c.

24
00:01:17,155 --> 00:01:21,740
The Auralin and Novodra columns contain many useful information points.

25
00:01:21,740 --> 00:01:24,770
The first number before the dash in this column is

26
00:01:24,770 --> 00:01:27,020
the baseline median daily dose of

27
00:01:27,020 --> 00:01:31,370
insulin from the week prior to switching to Auralin or Novodra.

28
00:01:31,370 --> 00:01:33,920
The second number after the dash is

29
00:01:33,920 --> 00:01:38,510
the ending median daily dose of insulin at the end of the 24 weeks of treatment.

30
00:01:38,510 --> 00:01:41,660
Now both are measured in units, short-form u,

31
00:01:41,660 --> 00:01:45,740
which is the international unit of measurement and the standard measurement for insulin.

32
00:01:45,740 --> 00:01:48,690
TheHbA1c start column is

33
00:01:48,690 --> 00:01:52,750
the patient's HbA1c level at the beginning of the first week of treatment.

34
00:01:52,750 --> 00:01:55,910
Similarly, theHbA1c end column is

35
00:01:55,910 --> 00:02:00,400
the patient's hemoglobin level at the end of the last week of the treatment.

36
00:02:00,400 --> 00:02:03,620
Here our HbA1C change column is

37
00:02:03,620 --> 00:02:07,475
the change in patient's hemoglobin levels from the start of the treatment to the end,

38
00:02:07,475 --> 00:02:12,650
ie, it's theHbA1c start column minus HbA1c end.

39
00:02:12,650 --> 00:02:16,600
This variable is determining the effectiveness of our insulin.

40
00:02:16,600 --> 00:02:20,330
Finally, we have our adverse reactions table which is telling us

41
00:02:20,330 --> 00:02:24,050
the name of the patient and whether or not they had an adverse reaction.

42
00:02:24,050 --> 00:02:27,485
In this demo, we'll look at programmatic assessment of data quality,

43
00:02:27,485 --> 00:02:29,210
where we will use pandas, functions,

44
00:02:29,210 --> 00:02:31,655
and methods to reveal our data's quality.

45
00:02:31,655 --> 00:02:35,700
Here I'm going to start off this demo by importing the pandas library and loading

46
00:02:35,700 --> 00:02:38,060
in the synthetic Phase 2 clinical trial data

47
00:02:38,060 --> 00:02:41,275
set for the hypothetical oral insulin called Auralin.

48
00:02:41,275 --> 00:02:44,480
Here I'm loading our patients and treatments data tables

49
00:02:44,480 --> 00:02:47,860
using read CSV into a pandas DataFrames.

50
00:02:47,860 --> 00:02:50,540
In practice, programmatic assessment is often

51
00:02:50,540 --> 00:02:53,120
a combination of programming and visual inspection.

52
00:02:53,120 --> 00:02:56,540
Let's go ahead and kick-start this by looking at the treatments DataFrame,

53
00:02:56,540 --> 00:02:59,810
which has a number of variables that are corresponding to patient treatment.

54
00:02:59,810 --> 00:03:02,435
To take a look at the first few rows of our data,

55
00:03:02,435 --> 00:03:05,435
we can use the.head method that we're now familiar with,

56
00:03:05,435 --> 00:03:08,155
which by default prints the first five rows.

57
00:03:08,155 --> 00:03:12,200
Now, if we want to look at the last few rows of our data to validate it was

58
00:03:12,200 --> 00:03:16,430
loaded correctly and get a glimpse of how the data is at the end of the DataFrame,

59
00:03:16,430 --> 00:03:18,500
we can use the.tail method in

60
00:03:18,500 --> 00:03:22,325
a similar way which is displaying the last few rows of our data.

61
00:03:22,325 --> 00:03:27,110
Here's one other method for looking at rows in the DataFrame,.sample.

62
00:03:27,110 --> 00:03:31,550
Dot sample is an example method of non-directed programmatic assessment,

63
00:03:31,550 --> 00:03:33,230
which means randomly leveraging

64
00:03:33,230 --> 00:03:36,730
programmatic assessments without any directed goal in mind.

65
00:03:36,730 --> 00:03:41,015
Dot sample returns, a random sample of records from the table.

66
00:03:41,015 --> 00:03:44,345
In this case, for example df.sample returns

67
00:03:44,345 --> 00:03:48,530
one entry randomly from the dataset and df.sample 5,

68
00:03:48,530 --> 00:03:50,710
returns five random entries.

69
00:03:50,710 --> 00:03:53,210
It's easy to make incorrect assumptions

70
00:03:53,210 --> 00:03:55,775
from just viewing the head and tail of the dataset.

71
00:03:55,775 --> 00:03:58,655
Plugging samples randomly from everywhere

72
00:03:58,655 --> 00:04:02,050
helps you get a good understanding of the inners of datasets.

73
00:04:02,050 --> 00:04:06,920
Additionally, using programmatic assessments to view random samples of data can help you

74
00:04:06,920 --> 00:04:12,085
decide what to look for with more pinpointed visual and programmatic assessments.

75
00:04:12,085 --> 00:04:14,450
One issue with.sample is that

76
00:04:14,450 --> 00:04:17,240
random rows are picked each time that you run the function,

77
00:04:17,240 --> 00:04:19,825
so the rows are different every time.

78
00:04:19,825 --> 00:04:23,255
If you would like to ensure your implementation is reproducible,

79
00:04:23,255 --> 00:04:27,995
you can use random seeds with.sample and sending the random state to an integer.

80
00:04:27,995 --> 00:04:30,830
For example here I set the random state to two.

81
00:04:30,830 --> 00:04:33,455
If you run this code block multiple times,

82
00:04:33,455 --> 00:04:37,650
the row selected randomly do not change after each run.

